<worksheet xml:id="activities-logic-equiv">

<activity><p>
	Write an English language statement that has the logical form <m>\lgcnot (A \lgcor B)</m>.
	Then write one that has the form <m>\lgcnot A \lgcand \lgcnot B</m>,
	where <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are the same as in your first sentence.
	<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan" text="title" />
	say your two sentences are logically equivalent.
	Do you agree?
</p></activity>

<activity><p>
	What do you think
	<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan" text="title" />
	would say about <m>\lgcnot (A \lgcand B \lgcand C)</m>?
	Use propositional calculus to justify your answer.
</p></activity>

<activity><p>
	Use <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" /> to simplify
	<m> \lgcnot (p \lgccond q) </m>.
	(Begin by applying <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-cond">Rule</xref>.)
</p></activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-logic-equiv-cartesian-conditionals">
	<introduction>
		<p> Recall that a pair of coordinates <m>(x,y)</m> defines a point in the Cartesian plane. </p>
		<p> Consider the following conditional statement. </p>
		<blockquote><p>
			If Cartesian points <m>(a,b)</m> and <m>(c,d)</m> are actually the same point, then <m>a = c</m>.
		</p></blockquote>
	</introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-logic-equiv-cartesian-conditionals-related"><p>
		Write out the converse, inverse, and contrapositive of the above statement.
	</p></task>
	<task><p>
		You now have four conditional statements.
		For each of the four, decide whether it is true, and justify your answer.
	</p></task>
	<task><p>
		For each of the three new conditional statements from
		<xref ref="activity-logic-equiv-cartesian-conditionals-related" text="type-local" /> in turn,
		take the view that that statement is the original conditional, and decide which of the others are
		<em>its</em> converse, inverse, and contrapositive.
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-logic-equiv-construct-bicond">
	<introduction><p>
		In this activity, we will justify the equivalence
		<me> p \lgcbicond q \lgcequiv (p\lgccond q) \lgcand (q \lgccond p) </me>.
		So consider the statements <m>A = p \lgcbicond q</m> and <m>B = (p\lgccond q) \lgcand (q \lgccond p)</m>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-logic-equiv-construct-bicond-1">
		<p> Argue that if <m>A</m> is false, then so is <m>B</m>. </p>
		<p> Do <em>not</em> use the proposed equivalence above as part of your argument. </p>
	</task>
	<task xml:id="activity-logic-equiv-construct-bicond-2">
		<p> Argue that if <m>B</m> is false, then so is <m>A</m>. </p>
		<p> Do <em>not</em> use the proposed equivalence above as part of your argument. </p>
	</task>
	<task><p>
		Explain why the two arguments
		in <xref ref="activity-logic-equiv-construct-bicond-1" text="type-local" />
		and <xref ref="activity-logic-equiv-construct-bicond-2" text="type-local" />,
		taken together,
		justify the equivalence <m>A \lgcequiv B</m>.
		Do this <em>without</em> making any further arguments about the truth values of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>.
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<p> Consider the statements <m>p \lgccond (q_1 \lgcor q_2)</m> and <m>(p \lgcand \lgcnot q_1) \lgccond q_2</m>. </p>
	<p> Use propositional calculus and substitution to show that these two statements are equivalent. </p>
</activity>

</worksheet>
